graph

Class Graph<K>

  • java.lang.Object
    • graph.Graph<K>
  • Type Parameters:
    K - - Vertex key type. The key type should be immutable. The behavior of the graph is undefined if K is mutable and is modified after being added to the graph.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<K>, java.util.Collection<K>, java.util.Set<K>

    public class Graph<K>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Set<K>
    Graph implementation using adjacency lists (actually hashmaps for efficient retrieval). The graph is weighted (with non-negative integer weights only) and directional, and does not allow repeated edges or vertices. The graph does allow a single null key.

    Vertex is an internal class that is not visible outside the graph class. The only method of interacting with the vertices is through various functions that make use of keys. As such, the terms "Vertex" and "Key" are sometimes used interchangeably within the documentation.

    The parameter type K is used as the key for each vertex. The behavior of the class is undefined if K is mutable and is modified.

    Author:
    Reed Simpson. Based on work by Reed Simpson and Tim Snyder.

      • pathWeight

        public int pathWeight(java.util.List<K> path)
        Finds the total weight of a given path along existing edges.
        Parameters:
        path - - A list of vertices. The method traverses the vertices in order.
        Returns:

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Returns a string representation of the graph. The returned string has one line for each Key in the graph. Each line consists of the Key value's string representation, followed by a visual separator (the string " - ") followed by the string representation of each Key that is adjacent to the given Key with the weight of the connecting edge given in parenthesis. For example, a graph with two Keys "A" and "B" with an edge of weight 1 connecting each of them to the other would return the following string: "A - B(1)\r\nB - A(1)"
        Overrides:
        toString in class java.lang.Object
        Returns:
        The string representation of the graph
